article.headline: Beard scores 18 of 28 in fourth as Mystics squeak past Sun
article.linkText: Beard nets 18 of 28 points in fourth to rally Mystics
article.story: WASHINGTON -- Alana Beard scored 18 of her 28 points in the fourth quarter to rally the Washington Mystics to a 65-64 victory over the Connecticut Sun on Tuesday night. Coco Miller had 15 points on 6-for-7 shooting from the field to help the Mystics (15-17) snap a two-game losing streak and hold on to fourth place in the Eastern Conference. Washington increased its lead to 1 1/2 games ahead of fifth-place New York, which lost at Chicago. The Mystics host the Liberty on Thursday night. Margo Dydek had 17 points and 11 rebounds and Lindsay Whalen added 13 points for the Sun (17-14), who lost for just the second time in seven games. Asjha Jones scored 11 points and Douglas added 10. Connecticut, which has already clinched a playoff berth, dropped two games behind second-place Indiana -- the Sun's likely first-round playoff opponent. Beard's pull-up jumper with 1:08 remaining gave the Mystics a 65-62 lead. After the Sun pulled within one, the Mystics missed two shots to give Connecticut a final chance, but Douglas missed from the left corner with 2 seconds left. After trailing by as many as 13 points in the first half, the Mystics pulled within six at halftime and took their first lead of the game at 49-48 on Beard's short jumper to start the fourth quarter. Beard set a WNBA record by scoring all of her teams 18 points in the fourth quarter. Beard went 5-for-8 from the floor, including one 3-pointer, and hit all seven of her free throws in the fourth quarter as she outscored the entire Sun team 18-16. The Sun took a 62-61 with 1:57 remaining in the game on Douglas' layup. Beard then hit her final two free throws with 1:34 remaining and her short jump shot had the Mystics up three. After a poor shooting start on both sides, the Sun closed the first quarter with a 9-1 run to take a 17-9 lead. The advantage increased to 30-17 when Connecticut scored seven points in a span of 32 seconds, capped by Jamie Carey's 3-pointer with 5:18 remaining in the half. Dydek's two free throws maintained the lead at 34-21, but the Mystics went on a 9-2 over the final 2 minutes and pulled to 36-30 at halftime. Dydek finished the half with 12 points and seven rebounds while Miller led the Mystics with 12 points, hitting 4-of-5 field goals. Mystics All-Star forward DeLisha Milton-Jones left the court in the first half to receive stitches in her lip. She returned in the second half, but finished with a season-low two points. Information from The Associated Press was used in this report.
